Who deserves the celebrated sphere?

01:52:45.340 --> 01:52:49.340
Item. Young Pete toppled the Asian bar market.

01:52:49.340 --> 01:52:55.340
Item. Young Pete's science project caused spontaneous baldness across the Texas Panhandle.

01:52:55.340 --> 01:52:58.340
Item. Young Pete accidentally drained Lake Superior.

01:52:58.340 --> 01:53:00.340
His response?

01:53:00.340 --> 01:53:03.740
No comment!

01:53:03.740 --> 01:53:06.740
No comment? Grunge bag? Not good enough.

01:53:06.740 --> 01:53:08.740
Exit question. Who gets the ball?

01:53:08.740 --> 01:53:10.740
Young Pete? Wrong.

01:53:10.740 --> 01:53:14.740
Answer. Older Pete. Bye-bye.

01:53:14.740 --> 01:53:16.740
Mom had had enough.

01:53:16.740 --> 01:53:21.740
She wasn't going to let our family fall apart over a bowling ball.

01:53:26.740 --> 01:53:34.510
Honey, something wrong?

01:53:34.510 --> 01:53:39.510
See, my mom had a metal plate in her head from an accident she had when she was a kid.

01:53:39.510 --> 01:53:43.510
And they both knew it would attract every lightning bolt for miles.

01:53:43.510 --> 01:53:46.510
Come inside, right now!

01:53:46.510 --> 01:53:50.510
Not until you stop this war.

01:53:50.510 --> 01:53:55.510
I can't. He won't let me.

01:53:55.510 --> 01:54:01.510
If you don't stand up to your father, I'm going to blow myself to kingdom come.

01:54:01.510 --> 01:54:08.510
Dad had no choice. Maybe he didn't have the guts to face his dad, but he got another idea.

01:54:08.510 --> 01:54:28.240
Later that night, he snuck Rolling Thunder from the house and ran four hours to the Canadian Borger.

01:54:28.240 --> 01:54:32.240
Go on. What are you waiting for? You're free.

01:54:34.830 --> 01:54:36.830
Be like that!

01:54:36.830 --> 01:54:54.380
You took it!

01:54:54.380 --> 01:54:58.380
Maybe it was stolen. I thought I heard a noise last night.

01:54:58.380 --> 01:55:02.380
Spunky, have you done something?

01:55:02.380 --> 01:55:04.380
No.

01:55:04.380 --> 01:55:09.380
I know that look. You've done something. Tell Papa.

01:55:09.380 --> 01:55:12.380
What difference does it make?

01:55:12.380 --> 01:55:17.380
It's gone. Now we can get back to normal.

01:55:17.380 --> 01:55:27.380
But we all knew things would never be normal again, and that's when we heard it.

01:55:27.380 --> 01:55:35.620
Rolling Thunder!

01:55:35.620 --> 01:55:40.620
No one knew how it got back, but one thing was certain.

01:55:40.620 --> 01:55:45.620
We had to settle this thing once and for all.

01:55:45.620 --> 01:55:49.620
Sometimes the only way to stop a war is to fight the bloodiest battle ever.

01:55:49.620 --> 01:55:53.620
A battle so gruesome there can only be one undisputed winner.

01:55:53.620 --> 01:56:00.620
Me and Pete were going to stare.

01:56:00.620 --> 01:56:05.620
Not only were the stakes higher than any other staring contest,

01:56:05.620 --> 01:56:09.620
but the only way to lose was to smile, and neither of us felt like smiling.

01:56:09.620 --> 01:56:14.620
Must destroy. Must destroy.

01:56:14.620 --> 01:56:16.620
Pete!

01:56:16.620 --> 01:56:20.620
Artie understood the contest could go on for weeks, even years.

01:56:20.620 --> 01:56:23.620
So he decided to come to our rescue.

01:56:23.620 --> 01:56:28.620
You know what I've come for, grand puppy?

01:56:28.620 --> 01:56:33.620
The ball! The ball! Out with it, old man!

01:56:33.620 --> 01:56:43.480
You'll be sorry.

01:56:43.480 --> 01:56:45.480
Get this up there, families!

01:56:45.480 --> 01:56:47.480
Get her lover!

01:56:47.480 --> 01:56:52.070
Blue Legless Dog!

01:56:52.070 --> 01:57:12.370
This!

01:57:12.370 --> 01:57:15.370
The battle went on for hours.

01:57:15.370 --> 01:57:19.370
The ball was the fiercest foe Artie had ever tangled with.

01:57:19.370 --> 01:57:27.620
And in the end, the strong man went down.

01:57:27.620 --> 01:57:33.620
Foolish man, brave, but foolish.

01:57:33.620 --> 01:57:48.420
With Artie defeated, nothing could stop us from the madness of the final showdown.

01:57:48.420 --> 01:57:51.420
Two Pete's would enter that room.

01:57:51.420 --> 01:57:54.420
Only one would come out.

01:57:54.420 --> 01:57:57.420
It's not too late to stop.

01:57:57.420 --> 01:58:00.420
Quit stalling, Chunderhead! Make me laugh!

01:58:00.420 --> 01:58:03.420
And so it began.

01:58:03.420 --> 01:58:09.420
At first, we just stood there, probing each other for weaknesses.

01:58:09.420 --> 01:58:16.380
Then suddenly, Pete attacked with a barrage of face twitches and tongue swirls

01:58:16.380 --> 01:58:19.380
that normally would have obliterated me.

01:58:19.380 --> 01:58:23.380
But I was ready, and came right back with the Wisconsin ear wiggle

01:58:23.380 --> 01:58:26.380
I picked up last summer in Sheboyka.

01:58:26.380 --> 01:58:29.380
I caught him off guard, but he didn't crack a smile.

01:58:29.380 --> 01:58:49.940
The battle was raging.

01:58:49.940 --> 01:58:53.940
Meanwhile, my dad was fighting his own battle.

01:58:53.940 --> 01:58:57.940
It started when Grandpa brought out cookies and milk.

01:58:57.940 --> 01:59:01.800
Maybe we should go up there.

01:59:01.800 --> 01:59:03.800
No. I forbid it.

01:59:03.800 --> 01:59:06.800
The ball must be passed on.

01:59:06.800 --> 01:59:10.460
Nothing can stop it.

01:59:10.460 --> 01:59:12.460
Drink that.

01:59:12.460 --> 01:59:13.460
It's milk.

01:59:13.460 --> 01:59:22.010
The contest slogged on for hour after brutal hour.

01:59:22.010 --> 01:59:26.010
The way it was going, maybe it would last the rest of our lives.

01:59:26.010 --> 01:59:29.010
It was insane. It was inhuman.

01:59:29.010 --> 01:59:33.010
Without warning, both of us unleashed everything we had.

01:59:33.010 --> 01:59:45.220
While we faced off against each other,

01:59:45.220 --> 01:59:51.220
Dad finally got up the nerve to face off against his dad.

01:59:51.220 --> 01:59:53.220
Who ate all the cookies?

01:59:53.220 --> 01:59:56.220
You know what sugar does to your teeth?

01:59:56.220 --> 01:59:59.220
Come on out, weather. Who did it?

01:59:59.220 --> 02:00:02.220
You want to know who ate the cookies? You want to know?

02:00:02.220 --> 02:00:04.220
I'll tell you. I ate the cookies.

02:00:04.220 --> 02:00:07.220
And you want to know what else? I didn't finish my milk.

02:00:07.220 --> 02:00:09.220
What do you think of that?

02:00:09.220 --> 02:00:12.240
Spunky.

02:00:12.240 --> 02:00:14.240
My name is not spunky.

02:00:14.240 --> 02:00:17.490
My name is...

02:00:17.490 --> 02:00:20.490
This is my house, and my wife, and my kids,

02:00:20.490 --> 02:00:22.490
and that ball is out of here.

02:00:22.490 --> 02:00:24.490
This war is over!

02:00:24.490 --> 02:00:26.490
But it wasn't.

02:00:26.490 --> 02:00:29.490
Me and Pete were locked in a death stare

02:00:29.490 --> 02:00:31.490
that nothing could break.

02:00:31.490 --> 02:00:33.490
As the intensity increased,

02:00:33.490 --> 02:00:46.570
I started to hallucinate.

02:00:46.570 --> 02:00:49.570
And I know he was going through the same thing.

02:00:49.570 --> 02:00:52.570
Pete! Pete! Open the door!

02:00:52.570 --> 02:00:55.570
I didn't know how much longer we could take it,

02:00:55.570 --> 02:00:58.570
but then something happened.

02:00:58.570 --> 02:01:01.570
I was able to see Pete again for what he really was.

02:01:01.570 --> 02:01:04.570
And I realized after all those hours,

02:01:04.570 --> 02:01:07.570
I wasn't staring at my enemy.

02:01:07.570 --> 02:01:09.570
I was staring at my best friend.

02:01:09.570 --> 02:01:12.570
I guess Pete felt the same way.

02:01:12.570 --> 02:01:16.570
And finally, the sheer stupidity of what we were doing got to us.

02:01:16.570 --> 02:01:29.570
The battle for the ball was over.

02:01:30.570 --> 02:01:47.290
I was wrong to interfere with your family.

02:01:47.290 --> 02:01:50.290
And spunky, um...

02:01:50.290 --> 02:01:57.630
Dad, I'm afraid I used the power of the ball for evil.

02:01:57.630 --> 02:02:00.630
Instead of good.

02:02:00.630 --> 02:02:05.330
Well, I don't know about that, Dad.

02:02:05.330 --> 02:02:09.330
It did have the power to show you that your son had grown up.

02:02:09.330 --> 02:02:14.330
Maybe you'd like to stay around a while and get to know him, huh?

02:02:14.330 --> 02:02:19.330
Soon after that, things pretty much got back to normal.

02:02:19.330 --> 02:02:24.330
Pete moved back in, and somehow our bed was stronger than ever.

02:02:24.330 --> 02:02:28.330
Dad was free to avail himself of all the privileges of Delta,

02:02:28.330 --> 02:02:31.330
including drinking non-milk beverages.

02:02:31.330 --> 02:02:33.330
And as for rolling thunder,

02:02:33.330 --> 02:02:35.330
now that no one desired it anymore,

02:02:35.330 --> 02:02:38.330
it had lost most of its evil power.

02:02:38.330 --> 02:02:42.330
Even so, we didn't want to take any chances.

02:02:42.330 --> 02:02:47.330
So after Grandpa taught Artie how to toss it with a sacred Tibetan power jam,

02:02:47.330 --> 02:02:50.330
it was time to say goodbye.

02:02:58.330 --> 02:03:04.980
We never knew where rolling thunder went,

02:03:04.980 --> 02:03:06.980
or if it would ever come back.

02:03:06.980 --> 02:03:08.980
But one thing was certain.

02:03:08.980 --> 02:03:10.980
We had learned our lesson.

02:03:10.980 --> 02:03:14.980
And next time, if it ever returned,

02:03:14.980 --> 02:03:16.980
we'd be ready.

02:03:16.980 --> 02:04:12.670
Here at What Will Is Water World,

02:04:12.670 --> 02:04:15.670
to see what Kellogg's Rice Krispies say.

02:04:15.670 --> 02:04:17.670
Ross, did you say what? What?

02:04:17.670 --> 02:04:19.670
It says in your dreams.

02:04:19.670 --> 02:04:22.670
Kellogg's Rice Krispies cereal is a loud part of this complete breakfast.

02:04:22.670 --> 02:04:24.670
You want some Rice Krispies?

02:04:24.670 --> 02:04:27.670
Hey, what do your Rice Krispies say?

02:04:27.670 --> 02:04:29.670
Bea, what do I want to be?

02:04:29.670 --> 02:04:31.670
Okay, what do I do next?

02:04:31.670 --> 02:04:35.670
I'll tell you if you're making some Kellogg's Rice Krispies treats. Deal?

02:04:35.670 --> 02:04:37.670
Deal.

02:04:37.670 --> 02:04:39.670
Kellogg's Rice Krispies treats recipe.

02:05:04.010 --> 02:05:06.010
Chaos Cartridge! 300 kids will win!

02:05:06.010 --> 02:05:09.010
Details on mock battles are right for official rules.

02:05:10.010 --> 02:05:13.010
Not all cards are bound by the paper they're printed on.

02:05:13.010 --> 02:05:18.010
NBA basketball cards are going the out of control!

02:05:20.010 --> 02:05:38.950
NBA basketball cards breaking all boundaries, man.

02:05:44.400 --> 02:05:47.400
Every night, when you're sound asleep,

02:05:47.400 --> 02:05:51.400
something strange happens.

02:05:51.400 --> 02:05:56.350
Not only do your eyeballs keep moving,

02:05:56.350 --> 02:05:59.350
even though your eyes are closed,

02:05:59.350 --> 02:06:02.350
but the world keeps moving too.

02:06:02.350 --> 02:06:04.350
Somewhere far away,

02:06:04.350 --> 02:06:07.350
kids will never meet or climbing trees,

02:06:07.350 --> 02:06:10.350
riding bikes and melting garter snakes,

02:06:10.350 --> 02:06:13.350
while you're fast asleep.

02:06:13.350 --> 02:06:16.350
Maybe that's what bugs my brother Pete.

02:06:16.350 --> 02:06:18.350
While he's stuck in bed,

02:06:18.350 --> 02:06:21.350
the world keeps going on without him.

02:06:22.350 --> 02:06:26.350
It's as if millions of kids got a head start in a race,

02:06:26.350 --> 02:06:29.350
and Pete never had a chance to catch up.

02:06:31.350 --> 02:06:34.350
Which was exactly the way our mom wanted to keep it.

02:06:34.350 --> 02:06:38.350
That's why every night, at precisely 9 o'clock,

02:06:38.350 --> 02:06:46.260
a wriggly nightly ritual begins.

02:06:46.260 --> 02:06:49.790
Honey, it's bedtime.

02:06:49.790 --> 02:06:51.790
Why?

02:06:51.790 --> 02:06:53.790
Because it's 9 o'clock,

02:06:53.790 --> 02:06:55.790
and that's what time growing boys go to sleep.

02:06:55.790 --> 02:06:58.790
Mom's first reason for making Pete go to bed

02:06:58.790 --> 02:07:00.790
was always the easiest to counter.

02:07:00.790 --> 02:07:03.790
After all, what is there some international chart

02:07:03.790 --> 02:07:06.790
that dictates what time all 10-year-olds should go to bed?

02:07:06.790 --> 02:07:15.290
Why 9 o'clock? Why not 9-11 or 9-42?

02:07:17.290 --> 02:07:20.290
Do we have to go through this every night?

02:07:20.290 --> 02:07:22.290
I just want to know why.

02:07:22.290 --> 02:07:25.290
Because 9 o'clock is your bedtime.

02:07:25.290 --> 02:07:28.290
But why?

02:07:28.290 --> 02:07:31.290
And that's when she'd say the six deadly words

02:07:31.290 --> 02:07:34.290
that make every kid's guts boil.

02:07:34.290 --> 02:07:37.290
Because I said so. That's why.

02:07:37.290 --> 02:07:41.290
And just like that, it's over.

02:07:41.290 --> 02:07:44.290
But one night, as I watched my brother climb the stairs

02:07:44.290 --> 02:07:46.290
to his bedroom cell,

02:07:46.290 --> 02:07:50.290
I knew that it was more than just time for bed.

02:07:50.290 --> 02:07:52.290
It was time for Pete to shatter

02:07:52.290 --> 02:07:55.290
adult's grisly grip of power on the world

02:07:55.290 --> 02:07:58.290
and free kids everywhere.

02:09:04.340 --> 02:09:08.340
After 10 years, 4 months, and 27 days,

02:09:08.340 --> 02:09:12.340
my brother Pete had reached his breaking point.

02:09:12.340 --> 02:09:16.340
The injustice of bedtime was no longer acceptable to him.

02:09:16.340 --> 02:09:19.340
Pete was convinced that the bedtime rule

02:09:19.340 --> 02:09:22.340
was part of the international adult conspiracy,

02:09:22.340 --> 02:09:26.340
which operated in secret and kept adults in control.

02:09:26.340 --> 02:09:29.340
Well, I'll tell you what I do, Nancy.

02:09:29.340 --> 02:09:33.340
I buy the 2% and I tell them it's whole milk.

02:09:33.340 --> 02:09:36.340
They never know the difference.

02:09:36.340 --> 02:09:40.340
Hey, what they don't know can't hurt them.

02:09:40.340 --> 02:09:42.340
And even though Pete discovered

02:09:42.340 --> 02:09:44.340
why his cereal tastes like sludge,

02:09:44.340 --> 02:09:47.340
the bedtime rule remained a mystery.

02:09:47.340 --> 02:09:53.350
One more 9 o'clock bedtime and Pete would have imploded.

02:09:53.350 --> 02:09:57.350
He needed a scheme and he needed it fast.

02:09:57.350 --> 02:10:01.350
And Pete being Pete, he knew just where to look.

02:10:01.350 --> 02:10:05.700
He unleashed his plot on an unsuspecting world

02:10:05.700 --> 02:10:09.700
the very next night during a game of flashlight tag

02:10:09.700 --> 02:10:26.660
in our backyard, throwed in on his final victim.

02:10:26.660 --> 02:10:30.800
Good night, Clem.

02:10:30.800 --> 02:10:34.460
It's 9 o'clock, Pete.

02:10:34.460 --> 02:10:36.460
That's enough for tonight.

02:10:36.460 --> 02:10:38.460
It's bedtime.

02:10:38.460 --> 02:10:42.460
Pete knew it was now or never.

02:10:42.460 --> 02:10:44.460
No.

02:10:44.460 --> 02:10:46.460
You know what, honey?

02:10:46.460 --> 02:10:49.460
No, I'm not going to bed. I don't feel like going to bed.

02:10:49.460 --> 02:10:51.460
Oh, don't be silly, pumpkin.

02:10:51.460 --> 02:10:53.460
It's wet out here.

02:10:53.460 --> 02:10:54.460
Come on, let's go.

02:10:54.460 --> 02:10:58.460
I said no.

02:10:58.460 --> 02:11:01.460
I said yes.

02:11:01.460 --> 02:11:05.460
And I don't like the tone in your voice, young man.

02:11:05.460 --> 02:11:07.460
I love it.

02:11:07.460 --> 02:11:09.460
The battle lines had been drawn.

02:11:09.460 --> 02:11:12.460
Mom knew that the next move was hers

02:11:12.460 --> 02:11:16.460
so her brain kicked into strategic mom defense mode.

02:11:16.460 --> 02:11:18.460
Would she try reverse psychology

02:11:18.460 --> 02:11:20.460
a maneuver she was famous for

02:11:20.460 --> 02:11:22.460
or would she stall, bribe him

02:11:22.460 --> 02:11:28.800
or go for the jugular and bring dad into it?

02:11:28.800 --> 02:11:30.800
You want to stay up late?

02:11:30.800 --> 02:11:31.800
Fine.

02:11:31.800 --> 02:11:34.800
She went with the old standby.

02:11:34.800 --> 02:11:36.800
And how late would that be?

02:11:36.800 --> 02:11:38.800
9.15, 9.30?

02:11:38.800 --> 02:11:40.800
Later.

02:11:40.800 --> 02:11:42.800
Oh, really?

02:11:42.800 --> 02:11:44.800
Well, why bother coming inside at all?

02:11:44.800 --> 02:11:47.800
Why don't you just stay up all night?

02:11:47.800 --> 02:11:49.800
Okay.

02:11:49.800 --> 02:11:51.800
Mom was stunned.

02:11:51.800 --> 02:11:53.800
Pete had called her bluff.

02:11:53.800 --> 02:11:55.800
And mom knew right away

02:11:55.800 --> 02:11:57.800
that the only way out of her pickle

02:11:57.800 --> 02:12:02.140
was with the deadly double bluff.

02:12:02.140 --> 02:12:04.140
Why stop there?

02:12:04.140 --> 02:12:06.140
How about two nights?

02:12:06.140 --> 02:12:09.140
How about eleven?

02:12:09.140 --> 02:12:12.140
Eleven days without sleep?

02:12:12.140 --> 02:12:15.140
Yep, I'm going to break the world record.

02:12:15.140 --> 02:12:17.140
Is that so?

02:12:17.140 --> 02:12:22.460
Well, have a nice time.

02:12:22.460 --> 02:12:24.460
Pete had won.

02:12:24.460 --> 02:12:27.460
And his master plan was quickly made clear

02:12:27.460 --> 02:12:29.460
to claim for kids everywhere

02:12:29.460 --> 02:12:32.460
the Ghibli's world record for sleeplessness.

02:12:32.460 --> 02:12:36.460
Set in 1962 by 56-year-old housewife

02:12:36.460 --> 02:12:39.770
Van Hooten.

02:12:39.770 --> 02:12:41.770
If Pete could pull it off,

02:12:41.770 --> 02:12:44.770
he proved to mom and the entire known world

02:12:44.770 --> 02:12:46.770
that when it came to bedtime,

02:12:46.770 --> 02:12:50.770
he could play by his own rules.

02:12:50.770 --> 02:12:52.770
Pete's friends were so inspired

02:12:52.770 --> 02:12:54.770
by the idea of staying up

02:12:54.770 --> 02:12:56.770
eleven days past their bedtime

02:12:56.770 --> 02:12:58.770
that they too decided to go for the record.

02:12:58.770 --> 02:13:00.770
But what none of them realized

02:13:00.770 --> 02:13:02.770
was that they were playing right into

02:13:02.770 --> 02:13:04.770
the razor-sharp claws of the international

02:13:04.770 --> 02:13:06.770
adult conspiracy.

02:13:06.770 --> 02:13:09.770
My, uh, lippy's going to learn a little lesson.

02:13:09.770 --> 02:13:12.770
And you just will reach.

02:13:12.770 --> 02:13:14.770
Eleven days. Ha!

02:13:14.770 --> 02:13:17.770
I give them eleven hours tops.

02:13:17.770 --> 02:13:20.770
That choice, I kind of handed to her.

02:13:20.770 --> 02:13:23.770
I never would have thought of this one.

02:13:23.770 --> 02:13:25.770
Of course not.

02:13:25.770 --> 02:13:26.770
No parent would.

02:13:26.770 --> 02:13:28.770
No parent could.

02:13:28.770 --> 02:13:30.770
Because a plan so brilliant,

02:13:30.770 --> 02:13:33.770
so perfectly perfect as Pete's,

02:13:33.770 --> 02:13:35.770
could only have come from those

02:13:35.770 --> 02:13:37.770
other tastes of being powerless.

02:13:37.770 --> 02:13:39.770
Clem.

02:13:39.770 --> 02:13:44.170
Natasha.

02:13:44.170 --> 02:13:45.170
Pervis.

02:13:45.170 --> 02:13:47.170
Luby.

02:13:47.170 --> 02:13:53.230
Pink eye.

02:13:53.230 --> 02:13:56.230
The strongest man in the world.

02:13:56.230 --> 02:14:02.150
We are the Nightcrawler.

02:14:02.150 --> 02:14:03.150
Doos!

02:14:03.150 --> 02:14:05.150
Snappy name, my little vikings.

02:14:05.150 --> 02:14:07.150
Son, uh, happy.

02:14:07.150 --> 02:14:10.150
You know why we're here.

